13 is the latest approved patch-set.
No files were changed between the latest approved patch-set and the submitted one.
Can you please add a `Tested:` field with a brief description of how you tested this change?
Added a `Tested:` section
Acknowledged
Are you required to adjust the record IDs?  If not, it may help avoid some corner cases to just leave a gap at the deleted ID.
This change seems unrelated to the rest of the commit.  Does it need to be in this review?
It has been removed.
Acknowledged
Does this support if the record ID rolls over in the file?
It now decrements greater RecordIDs in other files.

This looks like it will still have issues if the record ID rolls over.

For example, it's possible for the IDs to be:
0xFFFD
0xFFFE
0x0001
0x0002

In this case, the decrement needs to cross the rollover in reverse.

Is this a case that the delete needs to cover? The IPMI spec, under Section 1.9, mentions that the SMS manages the SEL and argues that the SEL shouldn't act as a FIFO. In Section 17.5, it appears that the SEL will ignore events if it is full (assuming PEF and the Event Message Buffer are not implemented).

```
Is this a case that the delete needs to cover?
```
Maybe not.  We can discuss if this is a corner case that we want to leave broken.

However, the IPMI spec under Section 31 states:
Record IDs are handles. They are not required to be sequential or consecutive. Applications should not assume that SEL Record IDs will follow any particular numeric ordering.

Based on this, I think it is much safer to leave a gap than to adjust existing record IDs. Also, changing existing records could cause confusion for external users who have already collected the SEL before the delete.

My vote for this is to leave the record IDs unmodified and simply delete the requested entry leaving a gap.

I have made the change to leave the record IDs unmodified and simply delete the requested entry leaving a gap.

As for record ID rollover, I think we should remove the rollover and instead set the rollover flag when checking the SEL info as seen in Table 31-2 of the spec and ignore any further entries as implied by the spec in that section since it is the responsibility of the SMS or user to clear the SEL when it is full.
Since we restart the record IDs at zero after a clear, I'm okay with removing the ID rollover support as it shouldn't ever be used.

I have removed the rollover support and have getNewRecordId stop at 0xFFFF with the AddSEL functions not adding an entry if the new record ID is 0xFFFF. I will make a change in phosphor-ipmi-host to return an error if an entry is attempted to be added when the SEL is full.
Could you please make this change as a separate commit, so it can be viewed and searched individually in the history?
I have created the separate commit here: https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/phosphor-sel-logger/+/71020
Acknowledged
Do you need to remove the file, or will the rename below work alone?
I have it only do the rename now.
Acknowledged
Does this reload work if you delete the currently active rsyslog file?  Does the reload need to happen after the rename, so the file manipulation is completed before the reload?
I now perform the reload after all file manipulation.
Acknowledged

Won't you need to continue looping through all the selLogFiles to adjust the record IDs?

For example, if ipmi_sel.1 has IDs 1-10 and ipmi_sel has IDs 11-20.  If you delete ID 5, you adjust ipmi_sel.1 to be 1-9, but it looks like ipmi_sel still has IDs 11-20. If that is the case, then when you decrement recordId back to 20, you will get a duplicate ID on the next entry.
This has been added now.
Acknowledged

Thanks for the update.  It has resolved everything except the rollover case, which may be the most complicated.

Are you sure you need to adjust the record IDs?  We can confirm with the IPMI experts, but my understanding is that record IDs don't need to be contiguous, and it seems much simpler to just leave a gap at the deleted ID.

While the IPMI spec doen't specify that the Record IDs must be contguous, I am currently adjusting the record IDs because when the SEL entries are displayed using `ipmitool sel list`, they are assumed to be sequentially contiguous as seen here:
https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-host-ipmid/blob/f027bf0334b91de5c829d21082dd42b75b45a405/dbus-sdr/storagecommands.cpp#L826

If the record IDs are not contiguous, then the entries after the gap are not displayed. This is also an issue with the current SEL Record ID rollover implementation since there would be a gap from 0xFFFE to 0x0001 so it may stop printing the SEL once the 0xFFFE entry is reached.
That looks like a bug in `storagecommands.cpp`.  Bytes 2:3 returned from the "Get SEL Entry" command are the record ID of the next SEL entry which should be used to request the next record.
The global variable should go in the .cpp file.
Done

Does this work?  I thought the way it worked is rsyslog kept a file handle open on the file with the pointer at the current location.  If you rewrite the file like this with one line missing, wouldn't rsyslog continue pointing at the old "end of file" location?

Does the next write leave a gap in the file and continue working or result in some error?
Yes it works. There is no gap and the new entries are added as normal.
Acknowledged

The issue here is that, on startup, we initialize the record ID to the last one used and increment from there.  This change will introduce two issues:
1. This list is lost on restart, so we wouldn't be able to use all of the freed IDs.
2. If a freed ID is the last ID before a restart, the next ID will initialize incorrectly from that one.

Do you need to re-use the freed record IDs?  It would be simpler to just drop them completely and stop allowing new records when the record IDs reach 0xFFFE, as you proposed.
I see your point. A local cache is now used to determine the next record ID which is backed up to a file in the case of a restart.

I'm a little worried about corner-cases with this change.  This is a pretty big change to functionality that has been there for a long time.  Especially because it's only needed for a feature that most people won't use.

How hard would it be to put this change behind a build flag so those who don't need SEL Delete can keep the current record ID handling?
Done
Looks good except for one last comment about the call to initialize the record ID.
Maybe not critical, but could the open fail for some reason, here?
I don't think it would fail to open since the file was just created, but I could change the if into a while loop just in case.
I see.  It should be fine as it is.
`initializeRecordId()` should already be called at line 302 above, so we shouldn't need this change.  Or should this be `#ifdef SEL_LOGGER_ENABLE_SEL_DELETE`?
Yes, you are right, it should be `#ifdef SEL_LOGGER_ENABLE_SEL_DELETE`. Fixed.
Acknowledged
Looks good to me.  It's been open for a while without other feedback, so going ahead with +2.
